Problem 1: Visualizing Different Branches of Music (35 points)

Professor A. Clark is working with a dataset on songs from Spotify. Here is the dataset:

spotify = read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/zjbranson/315Fall2021/main/spotify.csv")

The data come from Kaggle here. The original data is very large: It contains data on almost 200,000 songs, where each song is automatically measured based on 11 characteristics:

  • acousticness
  • danceability
  • duration_ms
  • energy
  • instrumentalness
  • liveness
  • loudness
  • speechiness
  • tempo
  • valence
  • popularity

Most of the variables are fairly self-explanatory; a higher value denotes a higher amount of that variable (e.g., energy, danceability, etc.)

Professor Clarks dataset (spotify) does not contain information on all 200,000 songs; rather, it contains the average information of every song in a given year. For example, the first row of the dataset shows the average value of each variable for all songs released in 1920:

spotify[1,]
##   year acousticness danceability duration_ms    energy instrumentalness
## 1 1920    0.6312423    0.5157501      238093 0.4186996        0.3542185
##    liveness  loudness speechiness    tempo valence popularity   decades
## 1 0.2160493 -12.65402  0.08298367 113.2269 0.49821  0.6103152 1920s-30s

Note that there is the year variable, ranging from 1920 to 2021. We will mostly work with the decades variable, which denotes two-decade ranges for each song.

In this problem we will use dendrograms to visualize this dataset; in Problem 2, we will use principal component analysis.

  1. (10pts) Make two dendrograms of the spotify dataset: One using single linkage hierarchical clustering and one using complete linkage hierarchical clustering. When you do this, use the distance matrix of Euclidean distances amongst the 11 quantitative variables in the spotify dataset, and be sure to standardize your variables before doing so. (Note: The only other two variables in the dataset are year and decades. So, create a dataset that removes year and decades when computing the distance matrix.)

When you make your plots, be sure to plot a dendrogram type object in R (i.e., please use the as.dendrogram function before plotting). Its okay if your plot has leaf labels.

First, well create a distance matrix for the quantitative variables:

# first, grab just the quantitative variables
spotify.subset = subset(spotify, select = -c(year, decades))

# standardize the variables
spotify.subset = apply(spotify.subset, MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x) x/sd(x))
spotify.subset = as.data.frame(spotify.subset)

#compute the distance matrix
dist.spotify = dist(spotify.subset)

Then, we can create the two desired dendrograms:

#run hierarchical clustering
hc.spotify.single = hclust(dist.spotify, method = "single")
hc.spotify.complete = hclust(dist.spotify, method = "complete")
#convert to dendrograms
hc.spotify.single.dend = as.dendrogram(hc.spotify.single)
hc.spotify.complete.dend = as.dendrogram(hc.spotify.complete)
#make the dendrogram plots
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(hc.spotify.single.dend, main = "Single Linkage")
plot(hc.spotify.complete.dend, main = "Complete Linkage")

After youve made your two plots, in 1-2 sentences, compare the overall shape of the tree (i.e., the clustering structure) between the single linkage tree and the complete linkage tree.

First looking at the single linkage plot, it seems like single linkage tends to create very small clusters: Looking at the left-hand side of that plot, it seems like there are about ten clusters with only one or two observations, and it isnt until the middle of the plot that it seems like there are clusters with multiple observations. Meanwhile, complete linkage appears to generate around three clusters, where there is about an equal number observations in each cluster. Furthermore, it is notable that subjects are clustered together much earlier on for single linkage than complete linkage (because the y-axis for the single linkage plot is much smaller than the y-axis for the complete linkage plot). This is intuitive, because single linkage clusters subjects based on the minimum pairwise distance, whereas complete linkage clusters subjects based on the maximum pairwise distance (as discussed in class).

Problem 2: The Principal Components of Music (40 points)

Now Professor Clark would like you to use principal component analysis to visualize the spotify dataset from Problem 1.

  1. (8pts) For this part, perform the following tasks:
  • Create a subset of the spotify dataset that only contains the 11 quantitative characteristics mentioned in Problem 1. Call this spotify.subset. (You should have already made a similar subset in Problem 1.)
spotify.subset = subset(spotify, select = -c(year, decades))
  • Run principal components analysis (PCA) on spotify.subset. Be sure that the columns of spotify are centered and standardized when you run PCA.
#center and standardize the columns
spotify.subset = apply(spotify.subset, MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x) x - mean(x))
spotify.subset = apply(spotify.subset, MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x) x/sd(x))
#note that, alternatively, you can just set center = TRUE
#and scale. = TRUE to center/standardize your variables.
spotify.pca = prcomp(spotify.subset, center = TRUE,scale. = TRUE)
summary(spotify.pca)

  1. (7pts) In class and lab we discussed using an elbow plot (or scree plot) to determine how many principal components should be used for visualization. For this part, create an elbow plot for these data, where the component numbers (1 through 11) are on the x-axis, and the proportion of total variation is on the y-axis.

One way to make the elbow plot is using the plot() function, as shown in the Lecture 17 R demo:

#Here is the proportion of variance accounted by each principal component:
varProps = summary(spotify.pca)$importance["Proportion of Variance",]
#draw the line
plot(1:ncol(spotify.subset), varProps, type = "l",
     xlab = "Component Number", ylab = "Proportion of Variation",
     main = "Elbow Plot")
#add the points
points(1:ncol(spotify.subset), varProps, pch = 16)

Alternatively, you could use ggscreeplot() within the ggbiplot R package:

library(ggbiplot)
ggscreeplot(spotify.pca)

After youve made your plot: Based on the plot, how many principal components do you think should be used for visualizations and analyses? Provide a 1-2 sentence explanation.

In any case, the elbow plot seems to clearly suggest that we should visualize \(k = 3\) principal components: After \(k = 3\), the line in the above elbow plot begins to level off quite a lot, thereby signaling that there is not much additional benefit (in terms of total variation) in adding more principal components in our visualizatoins/analyses. That said, a weaker argument can be made for \(k = 7\), because the proportion of variation certainly levels off at this point as well. However, by the time we get to \(k = 7\), the proportion of variation is already near 0. Furthermore, its worth noting that the purpose of PCA is to reduce the dimensionality of the data - going from 11 to 3 dimensions is certainly a large dimension reduction, but from 11 to 7 doesnt make our data visualization lives all that much easier. This is all the more reason to prefer \(k = 3\) over \(k = 7\).

  1. (15pts) Professor Clark now asks you to use ggplot() to make the following scatterplots:
  • A scatterplot with the first principal component on the x-axis and the second principal component on the y-axis, with points colored by decades.
#get the "rotation" from PCA:
rotation.pca = as.matrix(spotify.pca$rotation)
#Compute principal components, which is defined as X \times rotation:
prinComps = as.matrix(spotify.subset)%*%rotation.pca
#convert it to a data frame
prinComps = as.data.frame(prinComps)
#add decades to this data.frame
prinComps$decades = spotify$decades
library(tidyverse)

  • A scatterplot with the first principal component on the x-axis and the third principal component on the y-axis, with points colored by decades.
ggplot(prinComps, aes(x = PC1, y = PC3)) + geom_point(aes(color = decades))

Hint: This problem asks you to use ggplot() specifically to make the scatterplots; the Lecture 17 R demo walked through how to use the base R plot() function and the ggbiplot() function to make scatterplots of principal components. In order to use ggplot(), youll have to put the principal components and the decades variable into a single data.frame.

In both plots, we can see that earlier songs tend to have lower values of the first principal component: Songs from the 1920s to 1950s are on the left side of the plot, while songs from the 1980s to 2000s are on the right side of the plot. Meanwhile, in the first plot, we can see that songs from the 1920s to 1950s tend to have a lot of variation in the second principal component (in particular, songs in the 1920s tend to have lower values of this component), but other songs (from the 1960s onward) tend to have a second principal component value around 0. Finally, in the second plot, we can see a very interesting U shape: Old and recent songs both tend to have higher values of the third principal component, whereas sounds in the 1960s and 1970s tend to have a low value of the third principal component.

where spotify.pca is the object appropriately defined by prcomp(). You should be able to see an 11-by-11 matrix, where the rows correspond to the original variables and the columns correspond to the principal components. Each column represents the linear combination of the variables that each principal component represents (as discussed in class). In particular: Each number tells you how the variable is associated with the principal component. If a number is positive, that means songs with a higher value of that principal component also tend to have a higher value of that variable. Similarly, if a number is negative, that means songs with a lower value of that principal component tend to have a higher value of that variable.

Note that the sign of these numbers corresponds exactly to the direction of the arrows of the biplot; indeed, the arrows are simply a visualization of the two-dimensional vector in each row of this matrix. For example, we see that acousticness has a negative number for the first principal component (and thus it points to the left of the biplot) and a positive number for the second principal component (and thus it points upwards on the biplot).

Thus, using these numbers, we can make the exact same conclusions as we did above about decades and the 11 variables in the dataset. It is more tedious to stare at 22 different numbers in this rotation matrix, but this demonstrates another way that you can ascertain how the principal components are related to the original variables in your data, and thus how a variable like decades is related to other variables in your data as well.
